{{Infobox publisher | name = Éditions Robert Laffont | image = | caption = | parent = [[Editis]] | status = | traded_as = | predecessor = | founded = 1941 | founder = Robert Laffont | successor = | country = France | headquarters = | distribution = | keypeople = | publications = Books | topics = | genre = | imprints = | revenue = | owner = | numemployees = | website = {{URL|http://www.laffont.fr}} }}
'''Éditions Robert Laffont''' is a book publishing company in [[France]] founded in 1941 by Robert Laffont. Its publications are distributed in almost all francophone countries, but mainly in [[France]], [[Canada]] and in [[Belgium]].
It is considered as one of the most important French publishing houses. Imprints belonging to Éditions Robert Laffont include éditions [[Éditions Julliard|Julliard]], [[les Seghers]], [[Foreign Rights]] and [[NiL Éditions]]. In 1990, Éditions Robert Laffont was acquired by the French publishing group [[Groupe de La Cité]]. It is now part of [[Editis]].
Éditions Robert Laffont published the ''[[Quid (encyclopedia)|Quid]]'' encyclopedia from 1975 to 2007, but announced that the 2008 edition of the encyclopedia would not be published after annual sales had fallen from a high of 400,000 to less than 100,000, apparently because of competition from online information sources such as [[Wikipedia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/europe/frances-favourite-encyclopaedia-falls-victim-to-wikipedia-784420.html |publisher=The Independent |date= 20 February 2008 |title=France's favourite encyclopaedia falls victim to Wikipedia |last=Lichfield |first=John |location=Paris}}</ref>
